purely conceptually, are both cardinal and ordinal social welfare functions orderings?
Not exactly - this is an important distinction in social choice theory:

Ordinal Social Welfare Functions:
- Deal only with rankings/orders (1st, 2nd, 3rd...)
- Don't consider intensity of preferences
- Example: "I prefer A to B to C" (just the order matters)
- Are always orderings by definition
- Arrow's framework deals primarily with these

Cardinal Social Welfare Functions:
- Deal with numerical utilities/values
- Consider intensity of preferences
- Example: "I value A at 10 utils, B at 5 utils, C at 2 utils"
- Can be converted to orderings (by ranking the utilities)
- But contain more information than just orderings
- Used in utilitarian approaches

So while cardinal welfare functions can be used to create orderings (by comparing utilities), they fundamentally contain more information than pure orderings. This is why:
- Arrow's Impossibility Theorem applies to ordinal frameworks
- Many of the challenges with ordinal approaches can be avoided using cardinal utilities
- But cardinal utilities raise their own measurement and interpersonal comparison issues

