generics vs Box<T>
Here's a key comparison between generics and Box<T> in Rust:

Generics:
```rust
// Compile-time, zero-cost abstraction
fn process<T>(item: T) {
    // Size known at compile time
    // Each type gets its own specialized version
}

// Creates different versions for different types
process(5);         // i32 version
process("hello");   // &str version
```

Box<T>:
```rust
// Runtime, heap-allocated dynamic dispatch
fn process(item: Box<dyn Trait>) {
    // Size unknown at compile time
    // Single version that works with any type implementing Trait
}

// All calls use same function, with runtime lookup
process(Box::new(SomeType));
process(Box::new(OtherType));
```

Key Differences:
1. Memory Location
- Generics: Stack (usually)
- Box<T>: Heap (always)

2. Size Knowledge
- Generics: Known at compile time
- Box<T>: Only knows pointer size

3. Performance
- Generics: Zero cost abstraction
- Box<T>: Runtime overhead (allocation + indirection)

4. Code Size
- Generics: Larger (monomorphization)
- Box<T>: Smaller (single implementation)

5. Common Use Cases:
```rust
// Generics: When size is known/fixed
struct Vector<T> {
    data: T,
    length: usize,
}

// Box: When size is unknown/variable
struct TreeNode {
    value: i32,
    left: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
    right: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
}
```

