assert vs panic
Here's a comparison between assert! and panic! in Rust:

assert!:
```rust
// Testing and development
fn divide(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {
    // Debug builds only, removed in release
    assert!(b != 0, "Division by zero!");
    a / b
}

// Variants
assert!(condition);              // Basic
assert!(condition, "message");   // With message
assert_eq!(left, right);        // Equality
assert_ne!(left, right);        // Inequality
```

panic!:
```rust
// Runtime errors and unrecoverable situations
fn get_value(map: &HashMap<String, i32>, key: &str) -> i32 {
    // Always included, even in release
    if !map.contains_key(key) {
        panic!("Key not found: {}", key);
    }
    map[key]
}

// Common patterns
panic!("error message");
panic!("formatted {}", "message");
```

Key Differences:
1. Build Mode
- assert!: Debug builds only
- panic!: All builds

2. Purpose
- assert!: Development/testing conditions
- panic!: Unrecoverable runtime errors

3. Common Uses:
```rust
// assert! for invariants
fn process_age(age: i32) {
    assert!(age >= 0, "Age cannot be negative");
    // ... processing
}

// panic! for impossible states
fn get_first(vec: &Vec<i32>) -> i32 {
    if vec.is_empty() {
        panic!("Vector cannot be empty");
    }
    vec[0]
}
```

4. Best Practices:
```rust
// Prefer Result over panic!
fn fallible_operation() -> Result<(), String> {
    if something_wrong {
        return Err("Operation failed".to_string());
    }
    Ok(())
}

// Use assert! for testing
#[test]
fn test_operation() {
    assert_eq!(calculate(2, 2), 4);
}
```

The main guideline is:
- Use assert! for development-time checks
- Use Result for recoverable errors
- Use panic! for truly unrecoverable situations

